      {
        "id": "4e50e66c60d43c4eb37636595e8470c7516b101a",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-08 16:24:02.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1\n\nJim, if I understand correctly, the jackson annotations JsonIgnore, JsonProperty, etc .. are honored at serialization/deserialization time.  Is my understanding correct?\n\nI think you had in the past counterpart annotations for GsonIgnore, etc .. but I think you abandoned that work.   I was wondering if you could resurrect it, as for a new class coded up directly with Gson, it may make more sense to just use them?   What are your thoughts?\n\nThere's also a question from Pam to answer about right jackson version, in case you missed it.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "5040f62dd4fb84a8564cba1b6b9290cf169b0958",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-08 16:43:11.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Jim, if I understand correctly, the jackson annotations JsonIgnore,\n > JsonProperty, etc .. are honored at serialization/deserialization\n > time.  Is my understanding correct?\n > \n > I think you had in the past counterpart annotations for GsonIgnore,\n > etc .. but I think you abandoned that work.   I was wondering if\n > you could resurrect it, as for a new class coded up directly with\n > Gson, it may make more sense to just use them?   What are your\n > thoughts?\n > \n > There's also a question from Pam to answer about right jackson\n > version, in case you missed it.\n\nJorge: yes, your understanding is correct, or it will be, once all of this code is put in place.\n\nAs for resurrecting the GsonXxx flavors, we should probably discuss that in the JIRA comments.  A given message stream should use one or the other, but not both.  Would you expect the stream using the GsonXxx flavors to follow the gson default behavior, or the jackson default behavior?  If the latter, then I would assume we'd want to migrate the jackson annotations to gson annotations for all classes in that stream.\n\nI couldn't find the 2.9.6 comment, so will have to look around a bit more.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "746b43a932f8c04daa3de990fe73a6d720fb501d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-08 18:34:16.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThanks for the explanation, agreed we can move comments to JIRA ticket, may be we can add the conclusion to the resolution of jira ticket.  You are expert on this area so I'll follow your guidance, but it seems to me more user friendly to have extensions, new Gson annotations, named for example \"@GsonJacksonStyleIgnore\", \"@GsonJacksonStyleProperty\" that follows the Jackson behavior.  The annotation name would make it explicitly clear.   I think this will allow replacing all existing Jackson annotations and the direct dependencies to Jackson libraries.  Otherwise unless it is really well documented, I think folks could get confused as gson may be used, but still jackson annotations would be honored.   I realize though that it introduces extra work, so that if it is significant it is a drawback.   Makes sense?   I am interested in hearing your thoughts on it.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "9e41bb8b2b015a3a0de31e4e7d2765b02847200f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-08 19:21:52.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: -Code-Review\n\n> Thanks for the explanation, agreed we can move comments to JIRA\n > ticket, may be we can add the conclusion to the resolution of jira\n > ticket.  You are expert on this area so I'll follow your guidance,\n > but it seems to me more user friendly to have extensions, new Gson\n > annotations, named for example \"@GsonJacksonStyleIgnore\",\n > \"@GsonJacksonStyleProperty\" that follows the Jackson behavior.  The\n > annotation name would make it explicitly clear.   I think this will\n > allow replacing all existing Jackson annotations and the direct\n > dependencies to Jackson libraries.  Otherwise unless it is really\n > well documented, I think folks could get confused as gson may be\n > used, but still jackson annotations would be honored.   I realize\n > though that it introduces extra work, so that if it is significant\n > it is a drawback.   Makes sense?   I am interested in hearing your\n > thoughts on it.\n\nI'm ok with that approach, but it will entail some rework, including rework of the code in this review.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
